EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Public Safety
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to requiring the New York City Police Department to report noise complaints on a quarterly basis.
EventItemMatterName: Requiring the NYPD to report noise complaints on a quarterly basis.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Housing and Buildings
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the Commissioner/Chief Executive Officer of New York State Homes and Community Renewal to amend the Rent Stabilization Code to disallow “preferential rents” that are not for the duration of the tenancy.
EventItemMatterName: Amend the Rent Stabilization Code to disallow “preferential rents” that are not for the duration of the tenancy.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Education
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the New York City Department of Education to regularly review the use and condition of transportable classrooms and to limit the amount of time that transportable classrooms are used in New York City public schools.
EventItemMatterName: Dept of Education to regularly review the use and condition of transportable classrooms and to limit the amount of time that transportable classrooms are used in NYC public schools.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Economic Development
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling for further improvement in the consideration of health impacts in the Administration’s decision-making relating to real estate development projects, plans, and policies, specifically by utilizing health impact assessments and by increased collaboration between the Department of City Planning, the Economic Development Corporation, and the Department of Health and Mental Hygiene.
EventItemMatterName: Improvement in the consideration of health impacts in the Administration’s decision-making relating to real estate development projects, plans, and policies.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Governmental Operations
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to extending whistleblower protection for officers and employees of city contractors and subcontractors.
EventItemMatterName: Extending whistleblower protection for officers and employees of city contractors and subcontractors.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Consumer Affairs
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to requiring certain information on notices of violation issued to food vendors.
EventItemMatterName: Requiring certain information on notices of violation issued to food vendors.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Governmental Operations
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to the receipt of mail by city agencies.
EventItemMatterName: Receipt of mail by city agencies.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Health
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling on the United States Congress to pass and the President to sign the States' Medical Marijuana Patient Protection Act, which seeks to reclassify marijuana as other than a Schedule I or Schedule II substance.
EventItemMatterName: States' Medical Marijuana Patient Protection Act.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Health
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to revoking a food vending license for certain violations.
EventItemMatterName: Revoking a food vending license for certain violations.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Environmental Protection
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to air quality monitoring for certain construction projects.
EventItemMatterName: Air quality monitoring for certain construction projects.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Housing and Buildings

EventItemMatterName: Requiring the reporting and publication online of certain information related to outdoor signs.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Housing and Buildings
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to creating additional penalties for illegal outdoor signs.
EventItemMatterName: Creating additional penalties for illegal outdoor signs.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Housing and Buildings
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to requiring the department of buildings to conduct semiannual inspections of outdoor signs.
EventItemMatterName: Requiring the department of buildings to conduct semiannual inspections of outdoor signs.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Civil Rights
EventItemTitle: Resolution condemning the senseless shooting of Trayvon Martin and the inadequate investigation that followed, expressing deep sympathy for the Martin family, and calling for a full and impartial investigation holding those responsible to account as well as an examination of “Stand Your Ground” laws nationwide and the role they play in the spread of illegal guns on New York City’s streets.
EventItemMatterName: Condemning the senseless shooting of Trayvon Martin and the inadequate investigation that followed.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Immigration
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the U.S. Department of Homeland Security to reverse its position that the Secure Communities program will be activated nationally by 2013, and to respect states like New York that have taken actions to rescind their participation in this program.
EventItemMatterName: U.S. Department of Homeland Security to reverse its position that the Secure Communities program will be activated nationally by 2013.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Transportation
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to permissible parking in front of private driveways.
EventItemMatterName: Permissible parking in front of private driveways.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Education
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the New York State Legislature to amend the State Education Law, in relation to mayoral control of the New York City public school system, by requiring that the respective Community Education Council approve a co-location or school closure/phase-out proposal before it may be presented for a vote by the Panel for Educational Policy.
EventItemMatterName: Requiring that the respective Community Education Council approve a co-location or school closure/phase-out proposal before it may be presented for a vote by the Panel for Educational Policy.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Health
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the New York State Legislature to pass and the Governor to sign legislation that would add an excise tax on sugar sweetened beverages.
EventItemMatterName: Add an excise tax on sugar sweetened beverages.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Health
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling upon the United States Food and Drug Administration to require warning labels on sugar sweetened beverages.
EventItemMatterName: Require warning labels on sugar sweetened beverages.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Governmental Operations
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the New York city charter, in relation to the democratic election of the New York City police commissioner.
EventItemMatterName: Democratic election of the New York City police commissioner.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Public Safety
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling on the United States Congress to pass H.R. 3618/S.1670, the End Racial Profiling Act of 2011.
EventItemMatterName: Congress to pass H.R. 3618/S.1670, the End Racial Profiling Act of 2011.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Transportation
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to posting of truck route road conditions by the department of transportation.
EventItemMatterName: Posting of truck route road conditions by the department of transportation.

EventItemActionText: This Introduction was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Health
EventItemTitle: A Local Law to amend the administrative code of the city of New York, in relation to prohibiting the manufacture and sale of products containing synthetic cannabinoid.
EventItemMatterName: Prohibiting the manufacture and sale of products containing synthetic cannabinoid.

EventItemActionText: This Resolution was Referred to Comm by Council to the Committee on Health
EventItemTitle: Resolution calling on the United States Senate to pass and the President to sign the Dangerous Synthetic Drug Control Act of 2011, which would amend the Controlled Substances Act by banning synthetic cannabinoids commonly used in herbal incense.
EventItemMatterName: Dangerous Synthetic Drug Control Act of 2011

EventItemMatterName: Veterans Cemetery Bill (A.1386A/S.5381A)
